  "prompt": "What do Jews think of John the Baptist?",
  "response": "Jewish perspectives on John the Baptist can vary widely, as there is no single Jewish opinion. Historically, John the Baptist is considered a significant figure in Christianity, viewed as a precursor to Jesus. In the New Testament, he is depicted as a prophet who called for repentance and baptized Jesus.\n\nFrom a Jewish standpoint, John the Baptist is often regarded as a marginal figure. While some might acknowledge him as a Jewish religious leader of the time, his role in Christian theology typically limits his significance in Judaism. Jewish texts do not include him in their religious canon, and he is not a central figure in Jewish thought or tradition.\n\nAs a historical figure, scholars may note that John operated within a context of Jewish apocalypticism and prophetic tradition, which can be of interest in understanding the religious landscape of Second Temple Judaism. However, he is not widely mentioned or discussed in Jewish texts, and his baptismal practices and teachings are generally not recognized or followed in Judaism.\n\nOverall, while there may be some recognition of his historical existence, John the Baptist does not hold a prominent place in Jewish religious life or thought.",
